      "message": "I initially was confused and thought that there might be an \"off by one\" type error here because I thought that `u32 start` is the index of the first buffer to examine and `u32 end` is the index of the last buffer to examine. After looking closer, I don\u0027t think there is any error. It looks like the math is right and this will work correctly but the meaning of `u32 end` is not what I expected. It seems like end is actually either \"the index of the last buffer to examine + 1\" or \"the total number of vectors currently in the frame\".\n\nSince I got confused, it might be worthwhile to add a comment explaining it.\n\nOr maybe just eliminate `u32 end`. The only invocations of the function use:\n* start \u003d 0, end \u003d frame-\u003en_vectors in bufmon_count_buffers()\n* start \u003d pnd-\u003esnap[i], end \u003d f-\u003en_vectors in bufmon_dispatch_wrapper()\n\nSo it\u0027s always counting from some point in vector of packets to the end of vector. You could just pass in start and use n_vectors from the frame.\n\nThis is not critical, the code does look like it will work correctly. I just thought the meaning of end is slightly ambiguous.",
